article.headline: Stoudamire sparks Blazers' OT flourish
article.linkText: Blazers win fifth in a row at Orlando in OT
article.story:
ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- The Portland Trail Blazers are making a playoff push thanks to some players who aren't used to thinking about the postseason. Shareef Abdur-Rahim scored 14 points and played tough defense on Tracy McGrady, and Theo Ratliff tied a franchise record with nine blocks in leading Portland to a 94-91 overtime victory against the Orlando Magic on Tuesday night. It was the Blazers' season-best fifth straight win, evidence that the acquisitions of Abdur-Rahim and Ratliff from woeful Atlanta are paying off. "We're just happy to be in a situation where we have a chance to win every time we step out on the floor," said Ratliff, part of the Feb. 9 deal that sent Rasheed Wallace to the Hawks. "It's a situation where we have great guys around us, and they have taken us in with open arms." The Blazers' winning ways had Abdur-Rahim racking his brain for the last time he enjoyed such success. "We might've done it one time in Vancouver, I'm not sure," he said. Zach Randolph had 24 points and 12 rebounds, and Derek Anderson scored eight of his 18 points in overtime. Damon Stoudamire scored 17 with nine rebounds and seven assists. "It's not like it's a one-man team," said Anderson, whose 3-pointer at the start of overtime gave Portland a lead it never relinquished. "It's just understanding what they bring and what we have. We've always been able to do it, but the guys come in with veteran knowledge of, 'Let's play five-man basketball." The Blazers, since bottoming out to seven games under .500 (17-24) exactly one month ago -- the furthest below .500 they've been at the halfway mark since 1975-76 -- are 12-4. At 29-28, they are over .500 for the first time since Dec. 29. "We've still got a ways to go, we can't get content," Stoudamire said. "Even though we're winning games that we lost earlier in the year, we've got to keep on working, plugging away." The Magic, down seven late in regulation, sent the game into overtime tied at 83 on Rod Strickland's 3-pointer with 14.3 seconds to go. But Orlando missed nine of 13 shots in the extra period to fall short of winning four straight for the first time this season. It also was the Magic's first loss in four overtime games. The Magic's biggest miss came on Ratliff's huge rejection of Steven Hunter's dunk attempt that would've brought Orlando to 88-87 with 1:11 remaining. "That was a game-saver for us," Portland coach Maurice Cheeks said. The Magic had a slim chance of sending the game into a second overtime, but Keith Bogans' heave from the right baseline after a full-court pass didn't hit the rim. McGrady led the Magic with 31 points despite another subpar shooting night -- 11-for-32, including 2-for-14 on 3-pointers. Going back to his missed layup against Denver on Friday -- he was ejected soon after for kicking the ball into the stands twice -- McGrady has missed 39 of his last 53 shots. "He'll bounce back from that," Orlando coach Johnny Davis said. "It's just one of those spells." Strickland added 12 points and seven assists, and Juwan Howard had 10 points and 10 rebounds. The Magic shot 37 percent, and missed 17 of 20 3-point tries. But that didn't bother Davis as much as Orlando shooting 56 percent (14-of-25) from the foul line. "Three-point shots, often times, are contested," Davis said. "The free throw line, there's no one guarding." Anderson's 3-pointer with 3:51 left to go in the fourth quarter put the Blazers up 81-74. But Orlando rallied to tie on four free throws in six attempts, Strickland's reverse layup and his 3 with Randolph rushing at him.

Game notes
Ratliff tied the Portland record for blocks set by Bill Walton (twice) and Mychal Thompson. ... Portland is 5-2 in overtime games. ... The Blazers have a nine-game winning streak against the Magic. ... DeShawn Stevenson started as the Magic's small forward, the fifth player to take that spot in the lineup. The others are Bogans (whom Stevenson replaced), Gordan Giricek (for whom Stevenson was acquired from Utah), Britton Johnsen and Donnell Harvey. ... Randolph had his 33rd double-double of the season. ... Portland committed 20 turnovers, while Orlando had a season-low seven.
